> Actually, thinking for a bit, here's my actual take:
>
> This is, at least to some degree, the wrong problem. Overfocused
> at least. The problem isn't just boys doing poorly in school.
> Girls apparently feel like shit more frequently than boys.
> Immigrant children are more likely to quit school. Various
> minorities and majorities are doing poorly on various metrics,
> and focusing on the boys' plight distracts from the actual core
> problem, which is that schools are underfunded, teachers
> overburdened, and the students themselves are given very little
> incentive to go along with the entire thing.
>
> This could be at least on some level linked to the decision some
> decades ago to move operation of elementary schools from the
> state to the municipalities, without making any more money
> available to said municipalities. This was part of Tryggvi's
> party's bid to "lower taxes" and "reduce cost" =E2=94=80 by literally
> rolling the cost over to a different layer of government and
> having them deal with the problem.
>
> In general, this has been a trend in Iceland for about 40 years
> now =E2=94=80 I'd call it Reaganomics or Thatcherism, but both Reagan and
> Thatcher are dead while this policy is unfortunately very much
> alive. The political mood is that government should be run as a
> company, efficiency and cost savings matter more than outcomes or
> societal goals, and that anything that can be privatized should
> be privatized.
>
> So, like, I'm all for fixing boy's education, but let's start
> that journey by acknowledging that in order for things to be
> getting worse, they must have at some point been better =E2=94=80 and
> then let's analyze what actually changed.
